Caryn Dolley, News24#StateCaptureReport Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - Ex-arms deal consultant Fana Hlongwane somehow had access to one of former public protector Thuli Madonsela&rsquo;s official state capture investigation documents, before ever communicating with her office. This was revealed in Madonsela&rsquo;s report, which was made public on Wednesday, after President Jacob Zuma dropped his bid for an interdict to try and prevent its release.Hlongwane was allegedly a middleman in the Gupta family&rsquo;s attempt to offer Deputy Finance Minister Mcebisi Jonas the job of his boss, Nhlanhla Nene, in December last year.In the 355-page report, Madonsela said she received an &ldquo;unsolicited letter&rdquo; from Hlongwane on September 29.&ldquo;The title of Mr Hlongwane&rsquo;s letter&hellip; is consistent with the title I have used in all my correspondence relating to the investigation,&rdquo; she said.&ldquo;This indicates that Mr Hlongwane has had access to one of my official documents relating to the investigation prior to any correspondence with my office.&rdquo;Madonsela said that in his letter, Hlongwane said Zuma&rsquo;s son, Duduzane Zuma, told him that during a meeting involving Jonas, Jonas &ldquo;had made statements that I (Hlongwane) was blackmailing him&rdquo;.In his letter to Madonsela, Hlongwane said he asked Duduzane Zuma to urgently set up a meeting between the two of them and Jonas. Zuma set up the meeting at a hotel in Johannesburg.Blackmail storyAccording to Madonsela&rsquo;s report, Hlongwane asked that the meeting be moved to a private venue.&ldquo;At the private venue, the blackmail story was specifically raised with (Jonas). He (Jonas) stated that he had no recollection of any such blackmail conversations with anyone,&rdquo; Hlongwane wrote in his letter to Madonsela.A Gupta family member briefly entered the room where the meeting was held and then left.&ldquo;I categorically deny that there was ever a discussion or offer, by anybody, of any government position to Deputy Minister Jonas,&rdquo; Hlongwane said.Madonsela interviewed him on October 11.Hlongwane told her he had no relationship with Zuma, but was an &ldquo;uncle&rdquo; to Duduzane Zuma.Madonsela met Zuma on October 6 to get his response to the allegations Jonas made. She said he did not respond to her questions.http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/download-the-full-state-of-capture-pdf-20161102&nbsp; 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.